  "prompt": "Why do people with white skin get burnt easily?",
  "response": "People with white or fair skin get sunburned more easily due to lower levels of melanin, the pigment that gives skin its color and provides natural protection against UV radiation. Here are some specific reasons:\n\n1. Less melanin protection\n- Melanin acts as a natural sunscreen\n- White/fair-skinned people produce less melanin\n- Less melanin means less protection from UV rays\n\n2. Genetic factors\n- People with Northern European ancestry tend to have lighter skin\n- Genetic variations affect melanin production\n- Less melanin means more susceptibility to sun damage\n\n3. Skin type classification\n- Skin types I and II (very fair to fair skin) burn most easily\n- These skin types have minimal natural sun protection\n- Burn and tan minimally\n\n4. Physiological differences\n- Lighter skin contains less protective pigment\n- UV rays penetrate skin more deeply\n- More prone to cellular damage from sun exposure\n\n5. Increased risk factors\n- Higher risk of sunburn and skin cancer\n- More sensitive to sun damage\n- Require higher SPF sunscreen and sun protection\n\nThese factors contribute to why people with white/fair skin burn more quickly and easily compared to those with darker skin tones.",
